{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a87327b5-a868-4409-9a58-cdaa3235d9b7","content":"This is a known .NET breaking change on macOS related to DSA deprecation.\n\n## What happened\n\nDSA was marked obsolete (`SYSLIB0030`) starting in .NET 7. On macOS, .NET uses Apple's native Security framework for cryptography — which **never supported DSA**. Earlier runtimes kept a fallback path (OpenSSL shim or managed code), but .NET 11 removed it. Now `DSA.Create()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on macOS.\n\nLinux and Windows still work because they use OpenSSL and Windows CNG respectively, both of which still expose DSA.\n\n## How to fix it\n\nSince you only need to **verify** legacy signatures, switch to a managed implementation that runs everywhere:\n\n```bash\ndotnet add package BouncyCastle.Cryptography\n```\n\nThen replace the built-in DSA call:\n\n```csharp\n// Before (.NET 10) — breaks on macOS in .NET 11\nusing var dsa = DSA.Create();\ndsa.ImportParameters(legacyParams);\nbool valid = dsa.VerifyData(data, signature, HashAlgorithmName.SHA1);\n\n// After — works on all platforms\nusing Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto.Parameters;\nusing Org.BouncyCastle.Security;\n\nvar pubKey = new DsaPublicKeyParameters(\n    new Org.BouncyCastle.Math.BigInteger(1, legacyParams.Y),\n    new DsaParameters(\n        new Org.BouncyCastle.Math.BigInteger(1, legacyParams.P),\n        new Org.BouncyCastle.Math.BigInteger(1, legacyParams.Q),\n        new Org.BouncyCastle.Math.BigInteger(1, legacyParams.G)));\n\nvar verifier = SignerUtilities.GetSigner(\"SHA1withDSA\");\nverifier.Init(forSigning: false, pubKey);\nverifier.BlockUpdate(data, 0, data.Length);\nbool valid = verifier.VerifySig(signature);\n```\n\n**Long-term**: migrate signing to ECDSA or Ed25519. DSA is deprecated across the ecosystem and will only get harder to support.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a4502563-5640-4129-91cc-864f552762f0","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET compatibility issue with DSA (Digital Signature Algorithm) on macOS after upgrading from .NET 10 to .NET 11. Let me think about what I know about this topic.\n\nThis is a well-known breaking change in .NET. Starting with .NET 7 (and further reinforced in later versions), Microsoft has been deprecating and removing older cryptographic algorithms. Specifically:\n\nIn .NET 7, several older cryptographic algorithms were marked as obsolete with warnings (SYSLIB0022 for RC2, SYSLIB0021 for DES, etc.). DSA was part of this - `DSA.Create()` and related methods were marked with `[Obsolete]` diagnostics.\n\n\nOn macOS specifically, there's an additional layer to this problem. Apple's native Security framework doesn't support DSA, so .NET historically relied on OpenSSL through a compatibility shim to provide DSA functionality. However, Microsoft removed that OpenSSL dependency on macOS in recent versions, which means DSA support was effectively dropped on that platform. The breaking change in .NET 7 marked various cryptographic algorithms as obsolete, including RSA encryption/decryption with PKCS#1 v1.5 padding and other legacy algorithms. So the timeline makes sense now—DSA was marked obsolete in .NET 7, and by .NET 11 (which would be in preview in May 2026), the restrictions likely tightened further, especially on macOS where Apple's Security framework never supported DSA in the first place. The most probable cause is that .NET 11 removed DSA support entirely on platforms where the native crypto libraries don't back it.\n\nFor fixing this, if you only need to verify existing DSA signatures rather than create new ones, there are workarounds using managed implementations or alternative libraries.","outputTokens":1608,"requestId":"6814:29E277:110FCFD:156700C:69FFE345"},"id":"d33a3eb6-dfee-46df-bd12-960a1a37f0c6","timestamp":"2026-05-10T01:46:15.818Z","parentId":"4d7476fe-6d3c-4696-8cc9-a75d9e6eb5b3"}
